Al Jazeera’s Lucia Newman reports from Araucania region, Chile.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Renewed fighting between Thai and Cambodian forces has forced families near the border to flee, with bombs landing dangerously close to their homes. 
Children are experiencing fear and confusion amid the explosions. 
Despite a ceasefire agreement, uncertainty remains over when people can return. 
Humanitarian organisations are providing trauma intervention programmes to help children cope. Families also worry about relatives fighting on the front lines, while social media circulates images of soldiers’ funerals. 
The remains of some soldiers have been brought to evacuation camps, deepening distress. Displacement continues to weigh heavily, as communities struggle with fear, grief, and uncertainty.

Al Jazeera’s Barnaby Lo reports from Cambodia’s Preah Vihear province.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
A powerful storm system is battering the Gaza Strip, worsening already dire living conditions for hundreds of thousands of Palestinians sheltering in flimsy tents.
Heavy rain is flooding camp areas, with families digging trenches as water seeps into their shelters.
Israel continues to heavily restrict humanitarian aid, despite the US-brokered ceasefire, leaving critical shortages of proper shelter materials.
Civil defence teams warn residents to avoid damaged buildings after several unstable structures collapsed in Gaza City.
Up to 15 centimetres of rain is expected in 48 hours—nearly two months’ worth—deepening the crisis.
Aid groups say 1.5 million people are living in makeshift shelters and 300,000 mobile homes are urgently needed.

Al Jazeera’s Tareq Abu Azzoum reports on worsening humanitarian conditions in Gaza’s al-Mawasi area as flooding overwhelms families with no access to assistance.
Jonathan Crickx is Chief of Communication at UNICEF Palestine, who's in central Gaza at the
title: Unstoppable ‘nightmare’ as storm lashes displacement camp in Gaza

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
When Israel and the United States launched a 12-day war on Iran, Donald Trump hailed it as “one of the greatest moments in history”. More than 1,000 people were killed in Israeli strikes that ripped through homes, hospitals and even a prison during visiting hours.

Fault Lines travels to Iran to uncover the human cost of the conflict. We meet grieving families who lost loved ones, from 12-year-old Amir Ali and his father, to two-month-old Rayan and his parents — and follow the painful recovery of four-year-old Kian, who survived with life-altering burns. We also speak with the brother of Maryam Vahed Panah, killed in the attack on Evin Prison. The team secures a rare on-camera interview with Iran’s foreign minister as the country braces for the possibility of another war.

Target Tehran examines the motives behind the attacks, which Israel and the US claim were centred on Iran’s nuclear programme, and asks the pressing question: why now?

#iran #iranisraelwar #donaldtrump #benjaminnet
title: 12 days that shook Iran | Fault Lines Documentary

description:
A military court in Pakistan has sentenced a former intelligence chief to 14 years in prison. 
Retired Lieutenant General Faiz Hameed was found guilty on four charges, including violating the Official Secrets Act. 
He was arrested last year, after corruption allegations linked to a housing project. 
Hameed was appointed chief of the spy agency in 2019, when Imran Khan was the Prime Minister.
Hameed is widely seen as an ally of Khan, who was removed from office in a no-confidence motion and is in jail on multiple charges.           

Ayesha Siddiqa is a Senior Fellow at the Department of War Studies at King's College in London. She joins us from London to discuss the latest developments.

description:
The United Nations says Israeli soldiers have fired at peacekeepers on patrol in southern Lebanon.
No one was injured in the attack.
The peacekeepers say the Israeli military was informed in advance of the time and location of their patrol.
The UN has been working with the Lebanese army to support a year-old ceasefire aimed at ending fighting between Israel and Hezbollah.

Lebanese authorities say they're worried about what will happen when UN peacekeepers leave the southern border with Israel.
In June 2000, the United Nations established the Blue Line, a 120-kilometer withdrawal line. This was to confirm the complete withdrawal of Israeli forces after 22 years of military occupation in southern Lebanon.

Al Jazeera’s Zeina Khodr reports from Naqoura, southern Lebanon.

More than half a million people have fled the border region.
US President Donald Trump says he will speak to both sides on Thursday.

Pou Sothirak is a senior distinguished advisor to the Cambodian Center for Regional Studies, a foreign policy think tank.

An air strike in western Myanmar has killed at least 31 people.
Reports say the military bombed a hospital in Rakhine state.
At least 70 others have been injured. 
Rakhine is largely controlled by a rebel group known as the Arakan Army.     
There has been conflict in Myanmar since the military seized power in a coup in 2021.
The junta has often targeted rebel fighters with air strikes that have killed civilians.
The military has promised elections starting on December 28th, but rebels have pledged to block it from territory they control. 

Al Jazeera’s Tony Cheng is in central Myanmar and has more details on the strike.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The US House of Representatives has approved a bill to lift all sanctions imposed on Syria six years ago.
The proposal was included in the defence policy bill.
The Caesar Act was passed in 2019, to punish former president Bashar al-Assad's regime for human rights abuses.
The defence bill will now go to the Senate where it's expected to pass. 
Current president Ahmed al-Sharaa has been pushing the Trump administration to lift the sanctions.

The announcement has been met with scenes of joy in the Syrian city of Latakia. 
Crowds gathered to celebrate the vote.
Many view the lifting of sanctions as key to Syria’s economic recovery. 

Al Jazeera’s Mike Hanna has the latest from Washington, DC.

description:
Retired US Army Colonel Robert Hamilton explains that military personnel are required to refuse illegal orders under US law, military law, and international humanitarian law. From basic training to senior military education, service members are extensively trained to recognize and respond to unlawful commands. Hamilton highlights the precedent set by the Nuremberg Trials, emphasising that following illegal orders is not a defence. He also discusses the legal complexities surrounding recent US administration actions, including strikes against Venezuelan drug boats, and the role of Congress in authorizing military actions.

This is the second episode of 'Traces of Silk', a five-part series that looks at the legacy of the ancient Silk Road in Turkiye and the impact that history still has today.
